The Road to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Weapons of mass destruction and disarmament represent one of the most difficult challenges the world is currently facing. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that know no borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a universal good of the highest importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered under the devastation of conventional warfare and has been exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
However, such threat scenarios exist not only in Asia.
Although the use of nuclear weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that merely concerns the use of such weapons really sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Yet the UN plays a decisive role in this.
We offer a central forum in which states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and inform in order to achieve our agreed goals, and we advocate for them.
Most states have decided to give up nuclear weapons and have consolidated their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
Yet some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against a nuclear attack, which primarily explains the estimated 26,000 weapons still in existence.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and giving rise to new risks that nuclear weapons might be used.
The world is still concerned about the nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we may be facing a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is seen as a clean alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let's think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Peace Research), military expenditures rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating that the total cost of nuclear weapons alone in the United States exceeded $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
That is, by any definition, a massive investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the inherent dangers they pose have sparked a global intellectual movement, breathing new life into the idea of nuclear disarmament.
We have witnessed the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan established the International Commission for Disarmament and Non-proliferation.
Civic groups and states possessing nuclear weapons have also proposed suggestions, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own five-point plan.
First: I call upon all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, particularly the nuclear-armed states, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to undertake negotiations on effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
You could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed by the UNO.
I have sent a draft of such a convention to all UN members, which provides a good starting point.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with other countries on this issue at the UN disarmament conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiation forum for disarmament in the world.
The world would welcome a resumption of bilateral talks between the United States and Russia with the aim of significantly and verifiably reducing their nuclear arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in control research and development.
Britain's proposal to hold a conference of the atomic powers on the subject of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should begin discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly make it evident to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapon use or the threat thereof.
The Council could also call a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should halt their nuclear weapons programs and undertake their own disarmament obligations.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be permitted to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the CTBT into force, as well as momentum to enable the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without conditions initiate talks on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Moreover, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to finalize their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily implement the stricter security clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers frequently circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no significant estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various supplementary measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism using weapons of mass destruction, a limitation of the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new weapons bans, among others for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the atomic threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we are making it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks using weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a fresh start, not only for disarmament but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
